\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a region with a boundary defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and want to find the spectrum of a free particle confined to such a region,
 i.e.
 with boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(r(\theta),\theta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us write 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\theta\right)=c\rho\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is some length scale characteristic of the enclosure and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 a dimensionless function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wave function will be a superposition of plane waves with a given energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi(r,\theta)=\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi f(\varphi)e^{i\overrightarrow{q}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in the case of Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

o}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger's equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q=\sqrt{2mE/\hbar^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In polar coordinates, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{q}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}=qr\left(\cos\varphi\cos\theta+\sin\varphi\sin\theta\right)=qr\cos\left(\varphi-\theta\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To impose the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi f(\varphi)e^{iqr(\theta)\cos(\varphi-\theta)}=\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi f(\varphi)e^{iqc\rho(\theta)\cos(\varphi-\theta)}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A complete set of functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(\varphi\right)=\sum_{m}g_{m}e^{im\varphi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{m}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi g\left(\varphi\right)e^{-im\varphi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a function of two angular variables, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(\theta,\varphi\right)=\sum_{m,n}g_{n,m}e^{in\theta}e^{im\varphi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As such, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\psi\left(r(\theta),\theta\right) & =\sum_{m}f_{m}\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi e^{im\varphi}e^{iqc\rho(\theta)\cos(\varphi-\theta)}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{m,\,n}f_{m}h_{n,-m}(qc)e^{in\theta}=0
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{n,m}(qc)=\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\varphi e^{-in\theta}e^{-im\varphi}e^{iqc\rho(\theta)\cos(\varphi-\theta)}\label{eq:hnm_fourier_shape}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The boundary condition is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{m}h_{n,-m}(qc)f_{m}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The homogeneous linear equation (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hnm_fourier_shape"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) must have a non-zero solution given by a linear combination of the coefficient
s 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalues are determined by the zeros of the determinant of the matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{n,m}\left(qc\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det h_{n,m}\left(qc\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This matrix is infinite, but we can assume an approximation with a finite
 dimension and check the evolution of the eigenvalues as the basis size
 increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To parameterize the edges of regular polygon as a function of only 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, we want to write 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\theta\right)=c\rho\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we take the Fourier shape transform 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhang02acomparative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of the polygon to parameterize the edge.
 This transform has the coefficients
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{j\,\,m+b}=\left(\frac{m}{\pi\left(jm+b\right)}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{m}\right)\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is the summation index, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the number of sides and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 describes how the vertexes are connected (basically connecting the 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 neighbors).
 As such, we have the truncated series up to order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{k}\left(\theta\right)=\left|\sum_{j=-k}^{k}\alpha_{j\,\,m+b}e^{i(jm+1)\theta}\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 in the exponent can be factorized, as it has no dependence on the sum.
 Taking it out of the sum, its modulus is just 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 so it vanishes.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{k}\left(\theta\right)=\left|\sum_{j=-k}^{k}\alpha_{j\,\,m+b}e^{i(jm)\theta}\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression clearly displays a 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow\theta+\frac{2\pi}{m}$
\end_inset

 symmetry: by direct substitution, the new factor will just be 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i2\pi\cdot j}=1$
\end_inset

.
