\begin_layout Subsection
One-Dimensional Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first consider the well-known problem of the one-dimensional infinite
 potential well of size 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Let us also suppose that we want to write the solutions to this problem
 as a basis that satisfies boundary conditions.
 The simplest polynomial that goes to zero in the edges is just 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{1}\left(x\right)=N_{1}x\left(L-x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a normalization factor obtained simply from setting
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}dx\left(\phi_{i}\left(x\right)\right)^{2}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We now define the pre-normalization functions through Gram-Schmidt orthogonaliza
tion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hazewinkel_encyclopaedia_1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\phi}_{i}\left(x\right)=x^{i-1}\phi_{1}\left(x\right)-\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\braket{x^{i-1}\phi_{1}\left(x\right)}{\phi_{j}\left(x\right)}\phi_{j}\left(x\right)\label{eq:phi_i_generation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the scalar product is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{f_{1}\left(x\right)}{f_{2}\left(x\right)}=\int_{0}^{1}dxf_{1}\left(x\right)\cdot f_{2}\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

After orthogonalization, we finally normalize each function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{i}\left(x\right)=N_{i}\tilde{\phi}_{i}\left(x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Because every function will have a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 (by construction), they will immediately satisfy boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gram-Schmidt process ensures that each new basis function will be orthogonal
 to all previous ones.
 As such, we have the orthogonality condition we were looking for
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{\phi_{i}\left(x\right)}{\phi_{j}\left(x\right)}=\delta_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this basis, the Hamiltonian matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{ij}=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\int_{0}^{L}dx\phi_{i}\left(x\right)\cdot\left(\nabla^{2}\phi_{j}\left(x\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\pi^{2}}{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

 as we will use throughout this thesis, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{ij}=-\frac{1}{\pi^{2}}\int_{0}^{1}dx\phi_{i}\left(x\right)\cdot\left(\nabla^{2}\phi_{j}\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

and taking its eigenvalues after truncating the basis at 
\begin_inset Formula $i=12$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=\left\{ 1.0000,4.0000,9.0000,16.000,25.001,36.004,49.451,65.192,98.216,128.45,352.31,466.90\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As we can see, the lowest energy values match the expected ones for the
 one-dimensional infinite potential well.
 By increasing the number of polynomials used, we get better and better
 values for the higher energies.
 
\end_layout

