\begin_layout Subsection
Two-Dimensional Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of the two-dimensional problem, we need to write a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 that is analogous to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 that was used in the 1D case.
 Obtaining the initial polynomial does not present any problems: using the
 same logic as before, we can write it as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)=N_{1}\prod_{s=1}^{n}\varphi_{s}\left(x,y\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of sides of the polygon and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{s}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 are the line equations for the sides of the polygon.
 The normalization is defined the same way as before, but now taking into
 account the specific area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 we are integrating over
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{1}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\iint_{A}dxdy\left(\prod_{s=1}^{n}\varphi_{s}\left(x,y\right)\right)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These two expressions are easily generalized for any number of dimensions,
 having just to integrate over the hyper-volume element instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy functional matrix will be obtained in the same way, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{ij}=-\frac{1}{\pi^{2}}\iint_{A}dxdy\psi_{i}\left(x,y\right)\cdot\left(\nabla^{2}\psi_{j}\left(x,y\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To generate the higher order 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

s, we need to generalize Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phi_i_generation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 As we did in the 1D case, we again apply Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\psi}_{m}\left(x,y\right)=f_{m}\left(x,y\right)\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)-\sum_{i=2}^{m-1}\braket{f_{m}\left(x,y\right)\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)}{\psi_{i}\left(x,y\right)}\psi_{i}\left(x,y\right)\label{eq:GS_ortho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the scalar product is the same as the one used before, but now in
 2 dimensions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{\phi_{i}\left(x,y\right)}{\phi_{j}\left(x,y\right)}=\iint_{A}dxdy\phi_{i}\left(x,y\right)\cdot\phi_{j}\left(x,y\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The problem, now, is writing 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The method utilized by Liew and Lam 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liew_set_1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 sorts the multiplying monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}$
\end_inset

 according to the pattern 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ 1,x,y,xy,x^{2},y^{2},x^{2}y,xy^{2},x^{2}y^{2},x^{3},y^{3},x^{3}y,xy^{3},x^{3}y^{2},x^{2}y^{3},x^{3}y^{3},x^{4},y^{4},x^{4}y,xy^{4},\left(...\right)\right\} \label{eq:sortinG_fm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With this, we can define every 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}=N_{m}\tilde{\psi}_{m}$
\end_inset

 and use it to calculate the energy spectrum for the respective enclosure.
 The article mentioned above also includes a weighting function 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 that they associate with the thickness of the plates, but they take it
 as being 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as they study uniformly thick plates.
 As it does not make much sense to talk about the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thickness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a bi-dimensional shape, we omit it (i.e., we just replace it with 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization is highly inefficient, and scales with
 the basis size as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(n^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

, we would like to find a faster method.
 To do so, we utilize the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Orthogonalize[
\begin_inset Formula $\:\:$
\end_inset

]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 built-in method in 
\shape italic
