\begin_layout Section
Square Plane Enclosure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cartesian Coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this shape of enclosure, the solutions are trivial.
 As one can immediately apply separation of variables, we just have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi\left(x,y\right)=\sin\left(k_{x}x\right)\sin\left(k_{y}y\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the bottom-left corner of the square has been defined as the origin.
 In the top-right vertex (making the side of the square 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

), we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\psi\left(a,a\right) & =\sin\left(k_{x}a\right)\sin\left(k_{y}a\right)=0
\end{align}

\end_inset

If this condition is verified, the boundary condition in the edges 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a$
\end_inset

 are immediately satisfied.
 By the choice of the function basis, the edges with 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 already obey to the desired boundary condition.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{y}$
\end_inset

, this equation immediately gives a quantization of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{x,y}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{x,y}=n_{x,y}\frac{\pi}{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which, by direct application, gives the energy levels
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{n_{x},n_{y}}=\frac{\pi^{2}}{a^{2}}\left(n_{x}^{2}+n_{y}^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Which reduces to the well-known spectrum of the infinite square well
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=\frac{\pi^{2}}{a^{2}}\left\{ 2,5,5,8,10,10,13,13,17,17,18,20,20,25,25,32,\left(...\right)\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We will now compare this spectrum to the one we will obtain from the Orthogonal
 Plate Functions formalism.
\end_layout

