\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{4}$
\end_inset

 denotes rotations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}=C_{4}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 are the reflections on the two axis, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

 are the reflections on the diagonal symmetry axis of the square.
 Defining the invariant polynomial (the lowest order one that is zero on
 all boundaries) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\phi}_{0}\left(x,y\right)=\left(1-x^{2}\right)\left(1-y^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the tilde (~) identifies an un-normalized function.
 The higher order polynomials will be obtained by multiplication with a
 set of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n,i}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 that form irreducible representations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{4v}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 (is invariant under any symmetry operation), 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the same irreducible representation as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 denotes the order of this polynomial, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is merely an identifier inside each order of polynomials.
 Trivially, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 the only possible 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{0}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, there are only 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 possible first-degree polynomials.
 As we want them to be orthogonal, we write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{1,1} & =x\nonumber \\
f_{1,2} & =y
\end{align}

\end_inset

which are elements of the irreducible representation 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 With this knowledge, we can build the higher order polynomials recursively
 by taking products of this representation 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with the existing lower order representations.
 From this point on, we will require the direct product table for this symmetry
 group, reproduced in Table 
