\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, we want to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $E\otimes E$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the basic properties of decomposition, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\otimes E=A_{1}\oplus A_{2}\oplus B_{1}\oplus B_{2}\label{eq:ExE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This presents us with a problem: there are only three 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\mathrm{nd}}$
\end_inset

 order independent polynomials, but we have four irreducible representations.
 It becomes clear which is the one we can ignore when we write the three
 polynomials (obtained with regular multiplication of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,2}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{2,1}' & =x^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{2,2}' & =y^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{2,3}' & =xy
\end{align}

\end_inset

rearranging these, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{2,1} & =x^{2}+y^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{2,2} & =x^{2}-y^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{2,3} & =xy
\end{align}

\end_inset

which are all orthogonal amongst themselves.
 We can clearly see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,1}=x^{2}+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 is just the distance element, and is therefore obviously invariant under
 the action of any of the elements of the group.
 As such, it belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,2}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow-x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow-y$
\end_inset

 transformations (i.e., the action of the two 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 transformations) and changes signs under 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\rightarrow\left(\pm y,\pm x\right)$
\end_inset

 (i.e., the action of the two 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

 transformations), it must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 As for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,3}$
\end_inset

, its properties of invariance are the inverse of those of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Why are there no elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

? For the simple reason that one cannot make a 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\mathrm{nd}}$
\end_inset

 degree polynomial that is not invariant under both 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

, i.e., an anti-symmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\mathrm{nd}}$
\end_inset

 order polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, we again must apply 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to each one of these representations.
 Again with the assistance of the character table, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\otimes A_{1} & =E\nonumber \\
E\otimes B_{1} & =E\nonumber \\
E\otimes B_{2} & =E
\end{align}

\end_inset

Also, we will only have four 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{\mathrm{rd}}$
\end_inset

 order polynomials.
 The ones coming from the first product are quite simple, as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the invariant of the group:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{3,1} & =x\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{3,2} & =y\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

Of the two remaining polynomials, one should come from each one of the remaining
 irreducible representations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{3,3} & =\left(x+y\right)\left(x^{2}-y^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{3,4} & =\left(x+y\right)\left(xy\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

To see in which irreducible representation these fit, we can just apply
 the same procedure as before.
 With that, we see that they are not invariant or anti-symmetric under either
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 As such, they can only belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now finally onto 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

.
 We are, again, applying 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to itself, so we will have again Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ExE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 As we are in 
\begin_inset Formula $4^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 order, we will have five independent polynomials.
 Without any further thought, we already know one of them: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{4,1}=\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which obviously belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Building the other 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

s from 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{4,2} & =\left(x^{4}-y^{4}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,3} & =xy\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,4} & =\left(x^{2}-y^{2}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{4,5} & =xy\left(x^{2}-y^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,6} & =x^{2}y^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Unfortunately, we have one polynomial too many.
 Looking at the product table and at the initial irreducible representations
 that were used to obtain these functions, we know that both 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,6}$
\end_inset

 belong in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, along with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,1}$
\end_inset

.
 We can clearly see that these three functions are not independent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4\cdot f_{4,6}=f_{4,1}-f_{4,4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As such, the five functions will be 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,5}$
\end_inset

, and their irreducible representations are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{4,1} & \rightarrow A_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{4,2} & \rightarrow B_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{4,3} & \rightarrow B_{2}\nonumber \\
f_{4,4} & \rightarrow A_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{4,5} & \rightarrow A_{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can repeat this process up to any order, and the functions will be (by
 construction) orthogonal.
 Up to this order, the polynomials are grouped as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{0},f_{2,1},f_{4,1},f_{4,4} & \rightarrow A_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{4,5} & \rightarrow A_{2}\nonumber \\
f_{2,2},f_{4,2} & \rightarrow B_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{2,3},f_{4,3} & \rightarrow B_{2}\nonumber \\
f_{1,1},f_{1,2},f_{3,1}f_{3,2},f_{3,3},f_{3,4} & \rightarrow E
\end{align}

\end_inset

The polynomials will need to be orthogonalized amongst the same irreducible
 representation between different orders, and then normalized.
 After that, we multiply each one by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 to then insert into the energy functional and obtain the spectrum.
 By definition of the irreducible representation, the Hamiltonian matrix
 will be diagonal by blocks of each representation.
 Applying this method, we obtain the energies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{A_{1}} & =\left\{ 2.0000,10.038,20.691,36.575\right\} \nonumber \\
E_{A_{2}} & =\left\{ 24.317\right\} \nonumber \\
E_{B_{1}} & =\left\{ 10.037,36.571\right\} \nonumber \\
E_{B_{2}} & =\left\{ 8.0123,24.816\right\} \nonumber \\
E_{E} & =\left\{ 5.0029,5.0029,14.603,14.603,21.328,21.328\right\} 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the index denotes the irreducible representation of the generating
 polynomials.
 It is quite noteworthy that some of the degenerate levels come from different
 irreducible representations.
 It makes sense that some energy levels' degeneracy is separated between
 two different representations.
 Let us consider, for example, the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-times degenerate level 
\begin_inset Formula $E=10$
\end_inset

: one of the solutions is equivalent the expression (we are performing the
 expansion up to 
\begin_inset Formula $6^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 order)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\left(3\pi x\right)\cos\left(\pi y\right)+\cos\left(\pi x\right)\cos\left(3\pi y\right)
\]

\end_inset

where the other one comes from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\left(3\pi x\right)\cos\left(\pi y\right)-\cos\left(\pi x\right)\cos\left(3\pi y\right)
\]

\end_inset

Clearly, the first expression has the symmetries of the representation 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, where the second one has the ones from 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of the energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E=5$
\end_inset

, we have a different situation: the two original functions are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sin\left(2\pi x\right)\cos\left(\pi y\right)+\cos\left(\pi x\right)\sin\left(2\pi y\right)\\
\sin\left(2\pi x\right)\cos\left(\pi y\right)-\cos\left(\pi x\right)\sin\left(2\pi y\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which belong to the irreducible representation 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

