Cartesian coordinates are not the most natural choice to describe an hexagonal
 enclosure.
 As such, we choose the two basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{a}_{1} & =a\left(\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right) & \mathbf{a}_{2} & =a\left(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename agr_tese/hex.svg
	scale 33

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
New basis vectors.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can describe any point as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{r}=x^{1}\mathbf{a}_{1}+x^{2}\mathbf{a}_{2}=x^{\mu}\mathbf{a}_{\mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that both the inner domain and the boundary are easy to describe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is obvious that these coordinates are not orthogonal, but that is easily
 solvable.
 Taking the inner product, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{r}\cdot\mathbf{r} & =a^{2}\left(x^{1}x^{1}+x^{2}x^{2}+2x^{1}x^{2}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =g_{\mu\nu}x^{\mu}x^{\nu}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which means that the metric is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{g}=a^{2}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1/2\\
1/2 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{g}^{-1}=a^{-2}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
4/3 & -2/3\\
-2/3 & 4/3
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This means that the Laplacian is, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}=g^{\mu\nu}\partial_{\mu}\partial_{\nu}=\frac{4}{3a^{2}}\left(\partial_{1}^{2}+\partial_{2}^{2}-\partial_{1}\partial_{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the area element is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{2}\sigma=\sqrt{\det\left(\mathbf{g}\right)}dx^{1}dx^{2}=a^{2}\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}dx^{1}dx^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us look at the boundary.
 The six vertex coordinates are given by (starting at the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

 vertex and going around counter-clockwise)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(x^{1},x^{2}\right)=\left\{ \left(1,0\right),\left(0,1\right),\left(-1,1\right),\left(-1,0\right),\left(0,-1\right),\left(1,-1\right)\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For simplicity, we will now go back to using the notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(x^{1},x^{2}\right)\rightarrow\left(x,y\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

but we must remember that we are not working in Cartesian coordinates.
 The edge between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,-1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,0\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(x\left(\lambda\right),y\left(\lambda\right)\right)=\left(1,-1\right)+\lambda\left(0,1\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x & =1\nonumber \\
y & =\lambda-1\,\,\,\,,\lambda\in\left[0,1\right]
\end{align}

\end_inset

Repeating this process for the other five edges, we get the equations for
 the six boundaries
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\pm1, & y & =\pm1, & x+y & =\pm1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

as such, the inner region is defined by the conjugation of the three conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|x\right| & <1, & \left|y\right| & <1, & \left|x+y\right| & <1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constructing the first polynomial that vanishes at the boundary in the same
 way as was done in the case of Cartesian coordinates, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)=N_{1}\left(L^{2}-x^{2}\right)\left(L^{2}-y^{2}\right)\left(L^{2}-\left(x+y\right)^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The method for generating the higher order polynomials will be in the as
 before.
 The integrals over the region will now take the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\sum}d^{2}\sigma\rightarrow a^{2}\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\int_{-L}^{L}dx\int_{\mathrm{max}\left(-L,-L-x\right)}^{\mathrm{min}\left(L,L-x\right)}dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As this region is invariant under a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 rotation, so should be the polynomials.
 In this coordinates, a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/3$
\end_inset

 rotation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a}_{1} & \rightarrow\mathbf{a}_{2} & \mathbf{a}_{2} & \rightarrow\mathbf{a}_{2}-\mathbf{a}_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which means that, for a general 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{r}=x\mathbf{a}_{1}+y\mathbf{a}_{2}\rightarrow x\mathbf{a}_{2}+y\left(\mathbf{a}_{2}-\mathbf{a}_{1}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With this, the rotation matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
x'\\
y'
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -1\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and its inverse is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
-1 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x'\\
y'
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As such, the transformation of any function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\rightarrow g\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=f\left(\mathbf{R}^{-1}\cdot\mathbf{r}\right)=f\left(x+y,-x\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying this to our first polynomial, we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is invariant under a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/3$
\end_inset

 rotation, as expected:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{1}^{\prime}\left(x,y\right)=\left(1-\left(x+y\right)^{2}\right)\left(1-\left(-x\right)^{2}\right)\left(1-\left(x+y-x\right)^{2}\right)=\psi_{1}\left(x,y\right)\label{eq:invariant polynomial}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
