To generate higher order polynomials, we take
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{0}=A\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{2y}{L}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and multiply by a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi=A\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{2y}{L}
\end{array}\right]\mathcal{P}(y)
\]

\end_inset

Because the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 always remains, the boundary conditions will still be satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting spinors are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Psi_{0} & =A\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{2y}{L}
\end{array}\right]\\
\Psi_{1} & =B\left[\begin{array}{c}
y\\
-\frac{2y^{2}}{L}
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\braket{\Psi_{0}}{\Psi_{1}}=0
\]

\end_inset

Now, we can write a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\Psi_{i}}\hat{H}\ket{\Psi_{j}}\qquad i,j=0,1
\]

\end_inset

which we diagonalize to refine the obtained energy value.
 In this case, however, parity implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\Psi_{1}}\hat{H}\ket{\Psi_{0}}=B^{*}A(-i\hbar v_{F})\int_{-L/2}^{L/2}dyy\left(-\frac{2}{L}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

But in the next order
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{2}=C\left[\begin{array}{c}
y^{2}\\
-\frac{2y^{3}}{L}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

the only necessary Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization is between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the matrix full matrix becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{\Psi_{i}}\hat{H}\ket{\Psi_{j}}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1.5 & 0 & 0.381881\\
0 & 4.16667 & 0\\
0.381881 & 0 & 6.41667
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that, so that we obtain sensible energies when we
 increase the basis size, we must also consider the negative-energy (valence
 band) states both when generating the basis through Gram-Schmidt orthogonalizat
ion and when integrating the Hamiltonian matrix.
 These can be obtained, for the situation of the uniform boundary conditions,
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{n}=\sigma_{x}\Psi_{n}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{B}\\
\psi_{A}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be seen by explicitly applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 to the Hamiltonian (as they anti-commute, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma_{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is just the identity matrix):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{x}\mathcal{H}\sigma_{x}\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right) & =E\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right)\nonumber \\
-\mathcal{H}\sigma_{x}\sigma_{x}\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right) & =E\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right)\nonumber \\
-\mathcal{H}\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right) & =E\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right)\nonumber \\
\mathcal{H}\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right) & =-E\left(\sigma_{x}\Psi\right)\label{eq:sigmax_negative}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this, we can clearly see that the boundary conditions remain the same:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\psi_{B}}{\psi_{A}}=\pm1\implies\frac{\psi_{A}}{\psi_{B}}=\frac{1}{\pm1}=\pm1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

