\begin_layout Standard
The previous considerations assume the the medium confining the fermions
 is uniform.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 But we can envisage situations in which it varies from boundary to boundary.
 For instance we could have 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=L/2$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{B}=0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=+\infty$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-L/2$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{A}=0$
\end_inset

), the BCs corresponding to zigzag edges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "brey_electronic_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A ket that satisfies the imposed boundary conditions is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{0}=A\left[\begin{array}{c}
L/2+y\\
L/2-y
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that, due to the change of BCs relatively to the
 uniform situation, the negative-energy state will no longer be obtained
 by applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 to this ket, as it would switch the boundary conditions for their inverse.
 Instead, we obtain it by applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 as only switches 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{B}\rightarrow-\phi_{B}$
\end_inset

 and does not affect the boundary conditions (
\begin_inset Formula $-1\cdot0=0$
\end_inset

).
 Explicitly, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}^{2}=\mathrm{Id}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{z}\mathcal{H}\sigma_{z}=-\mathcal{H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{z}\mathcal{H}\sigma_{z}\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right) & =E\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right)\nonumber \\
-\mathcal{H}\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right) & =E\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right)\nonumber \\
\mathcal{H}\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right) & =-E\left(\sigma_{z}\Psi\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As such, the negative-energy state will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{0}=\sigma_{z}\Psi_{0}=A\left[\begin{array}{c}
L/2+y\\
-\left(L/2-y\right)
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:negative_1d_sigz}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exact solutions are easily guessed 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\phi_{A} & =A\sin\left(q(y+L/2)\right)\nonumber \\
\phi_{B}=\frac{1}{sq}\partial_{y}\phi_{A} & =sA\cos\left(q(y+L/2)\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

Imposing the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{B}(L/2)=0$
\end_inset

, we require that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\left(qL\right)=0\Longrightarrow q_{n}L=\left(2n+1\right)\frac{\pi}{2}
\]

\end_inset

Remarkably, this is the same spectrum as we obtained for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
