\begin_layout Section
Zero-Energy States in 2D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question remains: are there zero-energy states for the Dirac equation
 in a polygonal enclosure?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
States with exact zero energy are solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-i\left(\partial_{x}-i\partial_{y}\right)\psi_{B} & =0\nonumber \\
-i\left(\partial_{x}+i\partial_{y}\right)\psi_{A} & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset

These equation can be solved by a change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z & =x+iy & \bar{z} & =x-iy
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which means that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x} & =\frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\partial_{z}+\frac{\partial\bar{z}}{\partial x}\partial_{\bar{z}}=\partial_{z}+\partial_{\bar{z}}\\
\partial_{y} & =\frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\partial_{z}+\frac{\partial\bar{z}}{\partial y}\partial_{\bar{z}}=i\left(\partial_{z}-\partial_{\bar{z}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Adding and subtracting the two together, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\partial_{x}-i\partial_{y}\right) & =2\partial_{z}\nonumber \\
\left(\partial_{x}+i\partial_{y}\right) & =2\partial_{\bar{z}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these coordinates, the zero energy condition becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{z}\psi_{B} & =0\nonumber \\
\partial_{\bar{z}}\psi_{A} & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset

The general solution to these equations is simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\psi_{B} & =f\left(\bar{z}\right)=f\left(x-iy\right)\nonumber \\
\psi_{A} & =g\left(z\right)=g\left(x+iy\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the general solution for zero-energy states is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi\left(x,y\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
g\left(x+iy\right)\\
f\left(x-iy\right)
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As one cannot define a function of only 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}$
\end_inset

) that is zero along a straight line, it appears that boundary conditions
 can never be satisfied with this choice of ket.
 Consequently, no zero-energy states are possible using the Dirac equation
 in a polygonal enclosure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more specific example of this will be presented in the next subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

