\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Character-table-ofc6-1"

\end_inset

Character table of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{6v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{6}$
\end_inset

 denotes rotations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}=C_{6}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}=C_{6}^{4}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 are the reflections on the three axis that pass through the vertices, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

 are the reflections on the three axis that pass through the faces.
 Defining the lowest order polynomial (that is zero on all boundaries) as
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\phi}_{0}\left(x,y\right)=\left(\frac{3}{4}-y^{2}\right)\left(1-\left(x-\frac{y}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{2}\right)\left(1-\left(x+\frac{y}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the tilde (~) identifies an un-normalized function, we know that it
 belongs to the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 representation (shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant polynomial"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 As such, the product of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 belonging to the irreducible representation 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with this polynomial will also belong to the irreducible representation
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogously to the treatment for the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{4v}$
\end_inset

 point-group, the higher order polynomials will be obtained by multiplication
 with a set of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n,i}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 that form irreducible representations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{6v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trivially, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 the only possible 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{0}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, there are only 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 possible first-degree polynomials.
 As we want them to be orthogonal, we write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{1,1} & =x+y\nonumber \\
f_{1,2} & =x-y
\end{align}

\end_inset

which are elements of the irreducible representation 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 From this point on, we will require the direct product table for this symmetry
 group (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Direct-product-tablec6v"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename agr_tese/screenshot_2019-04-30--09-33-17.png
	scale 33

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Direct-product-tablec6v"

\end_inset

Direct product table for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{6v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, we have to be more careful than in the case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{4v}$
\end_inset

 group.
 Taking the direct product, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{1}\otimes E_{1}=A_{1}\oplus A_{2}\oplus E_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and we will have three polynomials.
 As the 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 irreducible representation is bi-dimensional and the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

s are one-dimensional, one of the elements must be ignored due to the symmetries
 of the shape in question.
 By direct product of the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,i}$
\end_inset

s, we have three polynomials
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{1,1}\times f_{1,1} & =x^{2}+y^{2}+2xy\nonumber \\
f_{1,1}\times f_{1,2}=f_{1,2}\times f_{1,1} & =x^{2}-y^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{1,2}\times f_{1,2} & =x^{2}+y^{2}-2xy
\end{align}

\end_inset

Reorganizing these equations so that they are invariant under the action
 of each of the irreducible representations, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{2,1} & =x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\nonumber \\
f_{2,2} & =x^{2}+y^{2}+4xy\nonumber \\
f_{2,3} & =x^{2}-y^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

again, these expressions were not yet normalized, but they are already orthogona
l amongst themselves.
 In what irreducible representation do each of them fall into? Obviously,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 must be in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 since it is the invariant distance in this space.
 We now need to classify 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2,3}$
\end_inset

.
 They must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

, as it is the only bi-dimensional irreducible representation we have in
 this order.
 Also, they are neither symmetric nor anti-symmetric under 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{d}$
\end_inset

, so they must belong to this group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, we will have four polynomials.
 Applying the direct product between 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\oplus E_{2}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{1}\otimes\left(A_{1}\oplus E_{2}\right)=E_{1}\oplus\left(E_{1}\oplus B_{1}\oplus B_{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 is invariant, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{3,1} & =\left(x+y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)\nonumber \\
f_{3,2} & =\left(x-y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us define two 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{\mathrm{rd}}$
\end_inset

 order polynomials that are orthogonal between each other
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
x^{2}y+xy^{2}\\
x^{2}y-xy^{2}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Orthogonalizing these with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,2}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{3,3} & =x^{2}y+xy^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{3,4} & =\frac{2}{3}x^{3}+x^{2}y-xy^{2}-\frac{2}{3}y^{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Do these functions belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

, or do they belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

? Taking their scalar product with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 we get the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\braket{f_{3,3}}{f_{1,1}} & \braket{f_{3,4}}{f_{1,1}}\\
\braket{f_{3,3}}{f_{1,2}} & \braket{f_{3,4}}{f_{1,2}}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This shows that these polynomials cannot be in 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\otimes E_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains an identity representation, and the integral over the volume of
 the identity cannot be zero.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,3}$
\end_inset

 is even under the reflection that swaps 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\rightarrow\left(y,x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,4}$
\end_inset

 is odd under this same reflection, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,3}$
\end_inset

 must belong in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,4}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now look into 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

, where we will have five polynomials.
 From the direct product table, we know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{1}\otimes E_{1} & =A_{1}\oplus E_{2}\nonumber \\
E_{1}\otimes B_{1} & =E_{2}\nonumber \\
E_{1}\otimes B_{2} & =E_{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 polynomial will be, as in the case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{4v}$
\end_inset

 group, the distance element square 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{4,1}=\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As such, the four remaining ones must be in an 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 irreducible representation.
 Two of them will come from linear combinations of products of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{4,2} & =f_{1,1}\times f_{3,1}-f_{1,2}\times f_{3,2}\nonumber \\
f_{4,3} & =f_{1,1}\times f_{3,2}+f_{1,2}\times f_{3,1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For the last two, we take the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,3}$
\end_inset

, and then orthogonalize both of them against 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4,3}$
\end_inset

.
 From this process, we arrive at (ignoring the normalization factors)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{4,2} & =\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+4xy\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,3} & =\left(x^{4}+x^{3}y-xy^{3}-y^{4}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,4} & =\left(27x^{4}+143x^{3}y-143xy^{3}-27y^{4}\right)\nonumber \\
f_{4,5} & =\left(9x^{4}-71x^{3}y-178x^{2}y^{2}-71xy^{3}+9y^{4}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

, we know we will have six polynomials.
 Taking again direct products of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 with the irreducible representation of the polynomials of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{1}\otimes A_{1} & =E_{1}\nonumber \\
E_{1}\otimes E_{2} & =B_{1}\oplus B_{2}\oplus E_{1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

From this decomposition, and as we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 is bi-dimensional, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 polynomials coming from both 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

s, and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 coming from each of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The first two are quite simple, as they come from applying the two elements
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 to the square of the metric:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{5,1} & =\left(x+y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{5,2} & =\left(x-y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now regarding the other four: one will have to be symmetric under 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}$
\end_inset

, one will be anti-symmetric under the same reflection, and the last two
 will not be either.
 Calculating them the same way as was done before, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{5,3} & =xy\left(x+y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)\nonumber \\
f_{5,4} & =\left(x-y\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)\left(2x^{2}+2y^{2}+5xy\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

From observation of the form of these last two polynomials, we know that
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{5,3}$
\end_inset

 must belong to the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 irreducible representation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{5,4}$
\end_inset

 must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For the last two, we repeat the same process that we used for the 
\begin_inset Formula $4^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 order, obtaining the two final polynomials for this order, which belong
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{5,5} & =xy\left(x+y\right)^{3}\nonumber \\
f_{5,6} & =xy\left(x-y\right)\left(x+y\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, let us obtain the 
\begin_inset Formula $n=6$
\end_inset

 polynomials.
 There are seven of them, and we can obtain them in multiple ways.
 For simplicity, we will act with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 in itself.
 The group products are the same as before, as we want to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(E_{1}\oplus B_{1}\oplus B_{2}\right)\otimes\left(E_{1}\oplus B_{1}\oplus B_{2}\right)=\left(A_{1}\oplus E_{2}\right)\oplus\left(A_{1}\oplus E_{2}\right)\oplus\left(A_{1}\oplus E_{2}\right)\oplus A_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Due to the symmetries of the problem, we will not have an anti-symmetric
 polynomial.
 Therefore, due to the dimensions of the irreducible representations, we
 will have one polynomial from 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $2+2+2)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The term that belongs in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 is again the distance in our coordinate system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{6,1}=\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, using the exact same procedure as before with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3,2}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{6,2} & =xy\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{6,3} & =\left(x^{2}-y^{2}\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The final four polynomials that all belong, by construction, to the irreducible
 representation 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

, are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{6,4} & =xy\left(x+y\right)^{2}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)\\
f_{6,5} & =xy\left(x^{2}-y^{2}\right)\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+xy\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{6,6} & =x^{2}y^{2}\left(x+y\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
f_{6,7} & =\left(x-y\right)^{2}\left(2x+y\right)^{2}\left(x+2y\right)^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can repeat this process up to any order, and the functions will always
 be (by construction) orthogonal.
 By definition of the irreducible representations, and as the Laplacian
 operator belongs also to the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 representation, the Hamiltonian matrix will be diagonal by blocks, with
 each block belonging to one irreducible representation, which significantly
 shortens the calculation time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to sixth order, the polynomials are grouped as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{0},f_{2,1},f_{4,1},f_{6,1} & \rightarrow A_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{3,3},f_{5,3} & \rightarrow B_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{3,4},f_{5,4} & \rightarrow B_{2}\nonumber \\
f_{1,1},f_{1,2},f_{3,1},f_{3,2},f_{5,1},f_{5,2},f_{5,5},f_{5,6} & \rightarrow E_{1}\nonumber \\
f_{2,2},f_{2,3},f_{4,2},f_{4,3},f_{4,4},f_{4,5},f_{6,2},f_{6,3},f_{6,4},f_{6,5},f_{6,6},f_{6,7} & \rightarrow E_{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

